sql:
SELECT DISTINCT model_type
FROM models
WHERE model_id NOT IN (
  SELECT model_id
  FROM user_model_access
);

SELECT model_id, dataset_id
FROM evaluation_metrics
WHERE mae < (SELECT AVG(mae) FROM evaluation_metrics);

SELECT model_name, description
FROM models
WHERE model_type = 'image classification' AND updated_at > '2022-01-01 00:00:00';

external_knowledge:
'sailed across the sea of 'CoCA'': refers to models that have been evaluated on the 'CoCA' dataset;
'average peaks in performance as measured by the F-measure': refers to the average of the maximum F-measure values for each model;
'F-measure': a statistical measure that evaluates the accuracy of a test by considering both the precision and the recall.

sql:
SELECT model_name
FROM models
WHERE model_id IN (
    SELECT model_id
    FROM evaluation_metrics
    WHERE max_fm > (
        SELECT AVG(max_fm)
        FROM evaluation_metrics
    )
);

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM model_comments
WHERE user_id = 'desired_user_id' AND model_id = 'desired_model_id';

SELECT models.model_name, models.version
FROM models
JOIN evaluation_metrics ON models.model_id = evaluation_metrics.model_id
WHERE evaluation_metrics.max_fm = (
    SELECT MAX(max_fm) FROM evaluation_metrics
);

external_knowledge:
'Cast their shadows upon' metaphorically means that the models have been paired or configured using the specified dataset, akin to a shadow being a sign of presence or influence. ;
'required_dataset_name' is the specific dataset name that the models are associated with through their configurations. ;
The association between models and datasets is facilitated through the 'model_configurations' table, serving as the bridge that connects these two entities. ;
In this metaphor, 'models' and 'datasets' can be thought of as characters in a narrative where 'model_configurations' determines the scenes in which they interact, highlighting the connection and interplay between them.

sql:
SELECT AVG(learning_rate)
FROM model_configurations
WHERE model_id IS NOT NULL;

SELECT models.model_name, model_comments.comment 
FROM models 
INNER JOIN model_comments ON models.model_id = model_comments.model_id;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT model_id)
FROM models
WHERE deleted_at IS NULL;

SELECT AVG(rating) AS average_rating
FROM model_ratings
WHERE model_id = 'specific model id';
